literature, and materials from U.S. and Brazilian government archives, Sarzynski shows how representations of the Northeast depended on persistent stereotypes depicting the region as backward, impoverished, and violent. By late March 1964, Brazilian Armed Forces faced little resistance when overthrowing democratically elected leaders in part because of the widely held belief that the violence and chaos in the "backward" Northeast threatened the modern Brazilian nation. Sarzynski's cultural history recasts conventional narratives of the Cold War in Brazil, showing how local struggles over land reform and rural workers' rights were part of broader ideological debates over capitalism and communism, Third World independence, and modernization on a global scale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aBrazil, Northeast-History-20th century. 0aBrazil-History-Revolution, 1964-Causes. 0aBrazil-History-Revolution, 1964-Propaganda. 0aCold War. 0aLigas Camponesas (Brazil)-History. 0aPeasantsxPolitical activityzBrazil, NortheastxHistoryy20th century. 0aPeasants-Political activity-Brazil, Northeast-History-20th century. 0aRural poorxPolitical activityzBrazil, NortheastxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural poor-Political activity-Brazil, Northeast-History-20th century. 0aSocial movementszBrazil, NortheastxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial movements-Brazil, Northeast-History-20th century. 4aBrazilian popular culture. 4aCold War. 4aNortheastern Brazil. 4acultural history. 4acultural representations. 4ainequality. 4aregionalism. 4arural social movements. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503605596zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/is